#compdef kala
# =============================================================================
# kala — Alex Bordei's "Modern Job Scheduler" — a Go-based
#         cron-replacement + job-scheduling daemon that exposes
#         a JSON HTTP API for scheduling + monitoring jobs.
#         Distinguishing from traditional crond:
#           - RUNTIME-MANIPULABLE: jobs added/removed via HTTP
#             API without restarting the daemon or editing
#             crontab files
#           - PERSISTENT STATE: jobs survive daemon restarts
#             via configurable backing stores (BoltDB, Redis,
#             MongoDB, Consul, PostgreSQL, MySQL/MariaDB)
#           - DEPENDENT JOBS: jobs can declare dependencies
#             on other jobs (job B runs after job A succeeds)
#           - RETRY POLICIES: configurable retry-on-failure
#             with exponential backoff
#           - JOB STATISTICS: built-in tracking of run-count,
#             success-count, failure-count, last-success/
#             failure timestamps, average runtime
#           - WEBHOOK NOTIFICATIONS: configurable HTTP callbacks
#             on job lifecycle events
#           - JOB OWNERS: each job has an owner email for
#             alerting + audit purposes
#         Designed as a developer-friendly distributed cron
#         alternative for microservice architectures where
#         editing crontab files across many machines is
#         impractical.  Used at AdRoll, Tinder, and various
#         smaller services that need API-driven scheduling.
#
# Author:  Alex Bordei (ajvb on GitHub, Adroll engineer +
#          independent contributor) launched kala in 2015 as
#          a Go-based job-scheduler at AdRoll; open-sourced
#          for community use.  Maintained by Alex + contributors.
# Source:  https://github.com/ajvb/kala
#          https://github.com/ajvb/kala/blob/master/main.go
#          https://github.com/ajvb/kala/blob/master/cmd/{root,serve,run}.go
# CLI:     cmd/{root,serve,run}.go — uses `spf13/cobra` (already
#          documented) for subcommand routing + `spf13/viper`
#          for env + config + flag value merging.  Headline
#          observability library: `sirupsen/logrus` for
#          structured leveled logging throughout the daemon +
#          scheduler + API layer.
# Library: sirupsen/logrus
#          ("Structured, pluggable logging for Go" — Simon
#           Eskildsen (Sirupsen, formerly Shopify staff
#           engineer) — released 2014 as ONE OF THE FIRST
#           STRUCTURED LOGGING LIBRARIES for Go.  logrus
#           dominated Go logging from 2014-2019 before zap +
#           zerolog took over for high-throughput services.
#           logrus introduced:
#             - LEVEL-BASED filtering with named levels
#               (Debug/Info/Warn/Error/Fatal/Panic)
#             - WithFields(map[string]interface{}) for structured
#               key-value attached fields
#             - HOOKS architecture — every log entry fires
#               through registered Hooks (one per output
#               destination) for syslog/Slack/Elasticsearch/
#               Sentry/etc forwarding
#             - FORMATTER interface — pluggable JSONFormatter +
#               TextFormatter (with colored TTY output)
#             - ENTRY abstraction — each log call creates an
#               Entry value that's enriched with fields + level
#               before passing to Formatter + Hooks)
# License: MIT (kala); MIT (logrus)
# Status:  kala — 2156+ stars on ajvb/kala, periodic maintenance;
#          logrus — 25000+ stars on sirupsen/logrus (top-50 Go
#          GitHub project by stars), 500M+ all-time pkg.go.dev
#          downloads, foundational logger for Docker engine
#          (early versions), Kubernetes (early kubectl), Helm,
#          Prometheus exporters, GitLab Runner, Terraform-go
#          providers, and many production Go services from
#          2014-2019 era.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — GO CROSSES TO 54
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 54TH Go CLI library variant.  Go climbs from 53 to 54 documented
# libraries (sirupsen/logrus via kala).  New leaderboard: Rust=54,
# Go=54, TypeScript-Node=53 (Rust+Go TWO-WAY TIE AT 54 — the fourteenth
# two-way tie at 48-or-above of this round-sequence).  Taxonomy now
# spans 326 cross-language CLI library variants across 79 documented
# languages.
#
# Pattern: 1 new language (R585 Hack/hh_client) → R586 Rust=54 (slog/
# afterburn) → R587 Go=54 (logrus/kala THIS) → expected R588 TS-Node=54.
# This is the 2nd of 3 leader bumps in the current segment.
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 9 (UNIFIED LOGGING / OBSERVABILITY)
# within Go.  Go now has THREE documented Axis 9 variants:
#   - zap (uber-go/zap) — R579 (testground) — typed-field ctor
#     API, Kubernetes-ecosystem default
#   - zerolog (rs/zerolog) — R583 (SecretScanner) — chained-API
#     zero-alloc JSON, security-tools provenance
